    "duration": "5",
    "pages": [
      [
        "Page 1",
        "In a little town lived a kind shoemaker named Hans and his wife, Greta. They made beautiful shoes together. But times were hard. One snowy night, Hans had only enough leather left for one last pair."
      ],
      [
        "Page 2",
        "Hans carefully cut the leather at his wooden bench. \"I'll sew these in the morning,\" he yawned. Greta brought him warm cocoa. They blew out the candle and tiptoed upstairs to bed."
      ],
      [
        "Page 3",
        "At midnight, the shop was quiet and dark. Then—tip, tap, tip-tap! Tiny feet came pattering across the floor. Something small was moving in the moonlight. But who? And what were they doing?"
      ],
      [
        "Page 4",
        "In the morning, Hans rubbed his eyes. On the bench sat the loveliest shoes he'd ever seen! Every stitch was perfect. \"Greta, come quick!\" he called. \"A wonder has happened in our shop!\""
      ],
      [
        "Page 5",
        "A rich man bought the shoes that very day and paid twice the usual price! Hans bought leather for two more pairs. That night, he cut the pieces and placed them neatly on the bench."
      ],
      [
        "Page 6",
        "Tip, tap, tip-tap! Again the tiny feet danced in the dark. By morning, two splendid pairs sparkled on the bench—tiny stitches, shiny buckles. \"Our luck has turned!\" Greta whispered, eyes wide with joy."
      ],
      [
        "Page 7",
        "Night after night, the magic kept coming. Hans cut the leather; morning brought beautiful shoes. Soon the little shop was busy and bright. But who was their secret helper? Hans and Greta just had to know."
      ],
      [
        "Page 8",
        "One frosty evening, Greta had an idea. \"Let's hide behind the curtain tonight and peek!\" Hans nodded. They lit a tiny candle, tucked themselves away, and waited. The clock went tick, tick, tick toward midnight."
      ],
      [
        "Page 9",
        "Bong! Midnight struck. Through a crack in the floor came two teeny elves, no taller than teacups. They wore ragged shirts and had bare little feet. They hopped onto the bench and got straight to work."
      ],
      [
        "Page 10",
        "Snip-snap went their tiny tools! Stitch-stitch went their nimble fingers! They hummed a merry elf tune as they worked. By dawn, a row of perfect shoes shone on the bench. Then—poof!—the elves were gone."
      ],
      [
        "Page 11",
        "\"Those dear little elves!\" Greta cried. \"Their feet must be so cold.\" Hans smiled. \"Let's make them a thank-you gift.\" They sewed tiny shirts, warm trousers, cozy caps, and two pairs of the softest shoes."
      ],
      [
        "Page 12",
        "That night, instead of leather, they set the tiny clothes on the bench. Then they hid and watched. At midnight, the elves popped up—and squealed with delight! They dressed in a twirl and danced about the shop."
      ],
      [
        "Page 13",
        "The elves laughed and leapt right out the window, waving goodbye. Hans and Greta never saw them again. But from that day on, every shoe they made was happy. And their little shop was cozy forever after."
      ]
    ],
