    "pages": [
      [
        "Page 1",
        "Once, a kind woman wished for a tiny child. A wise lady gave her a magic seed. She planted it, and a beautiful tulip bloomed. Inside, curled up like a petal, sat a girl no bigger than a thumb!"
      ],
      [
        "Page 2",
        "The woman called her Thumbelina. She slept in a polished walnut shell. Her pillow was a violet. Her blanket was a rose petal. \"Goodnight, little one,\" whispered the woman. Thumbelina smiled and sang the softest song."
      ],
      [
        "Page 3",
        "One night, a lumpy old toad hopped through the window. \"Ribbit! What a lovely little wife for my son!\" She scooped up the walnut shell and plopped it on a wide green lily pad in the river."
      ],
      [
        "Page 4",
        "Thumbelina woke up floating! The toad's son goggled at her. \"Blub, blub!\" he burbled clumsily. Thumbelina cried quiet tears. Kind fish below heard her and nibbled, nibble-nibble, at the lily pad stem until it drifted free."
      ],
      [
        "Page 5",
        "Away floated the lily pad, past reeds and shining water. A white butterfly swooped down. \"May I help?\" he fluttered. Thumbelina tied her ribbon to him, and together they sailed downstream, giggling. \"This is better than toads!\""
      ],
      [
        "Page 6",
        "Suddenly, a big shiny beetle swooped in and grabbed her. Whoosh! He carried her up to a leafy tree. But the other beetles sniffed. \"She has no wings! How odd!\" The beetle shrugged and set her gently down."
      ],
      [
        "Page 7",
        "Summer slipped into autumn. Thumbelina wandered the wide meadow, nibbling nectar and sleeping under mushrooms. Then cold winds blew. Snowflakes fell, fat and cold. Thumbelina shivered in her thin petal dress. \"Oh, I need a warm home.\""
      ],
      [
        "Page 8",
        "She found a tiny door in the ground. A plump field mouse peeked out. \"Come in, little thing! Have some soup.\" The mouse's burrow was cozy and crumb-filled. Thumbelina swept floors and told stories beside the warm stove."
      ],
      [
        "Page 9",
        "One day they visited Mole, the mouse's neighbor. In his dark tunnel lay a fallen swallow, cold and still. Thumbelina's heart ached. That night she crept back with a blanket of dry grass and tucked it around him."
      ],
      [
        "Page 10",
        "Thump. Thump. A heartbeat! The swallow was only sleeping through winter. All winter Thumbelina brought him seeds and kept him warm. \"Thank you, little friend,\" he chirped. When spring came, he flew up, up, and away."
      ],
      [
        "Page 11",
        "The mouse wanted Thumbelina to marry Mole and live underground forever. But Thumbelina missed the sun. She missed flowers. She missed the sky. She stood in the meadow one last time, whispering goodbye to every daisy."
      ],
      [
        "Page 12",
        "Swoosh! The swallow returned! \"Climb on my back, dear friend. I know a place for you.\" They soared over fields and mountains to a warm land of blossoms, where the air smelled like honey and every petal sparkled."
      ],
      [
        "Page 13",
        "Inside the biggest flower stood a tiny prince, just her size, with gentle eyes and gossamer wings. \"Welcome home,\" he smiled. The flower people cheered. They gave her shimmering wings, and Thumbelina laughed. At last, she belonged."
      ]
    ],
