    "duration": "5",
    "pages": [
      [
        "Page 1",
        "In a cozy little workshop lived a kind old woodcarver named Geppetto. He had no children, only tools and wood shavings. One evening, he began carving a special puppet. \"I shall call him Pinocchio,\" he said softly."
      ],
      [
        "Page 2",
        "Tap-tap! Snip-snap! Out came a little wooden boy with a round nose and a painted smile. Suddenly, Pinocchio blinked! He wiggled his toes and giggled. \"Papa!\" he cried. Geppetto's eyes shone with happy tears."
      ],
      [
        "Page 3",
        "A tiny green cricket hopped onto the windowsill. \"Chirp! I am Jiminy, your conscience,\" he said. \"I'll help you choose what's right.\" Pinocchio tilted his wooden head. \"What is right?\" he asked, curious as could be."
      ],
      [
        "Page 4",
        "Geppetto gave Pinocchio schoolbooks wrapped in brown paper. \"Learn well, my boy!\" Off skipped Pinocchio down the lane. But on the way, he heard drums and music. A puppet show! His wooden feet would not walk past."
      ],
      [
        "Page 5",
        "Pinocchio traded his books for a ticket. Oh, the bright stage! The dancing puppets! But the grumpy showman wanted to keep him forever. Pinocchio's heart thumped. \"Please, sir, let me go home!\" he squeaked, very frightened."
      ],
      [
        "Page 6",
        "The showman's heart softened. He gave Pinocchio five gold coins. \"Take these to your papa.\" On the road, a sly fox and a sneaky cat appeared. \"Plant those coins!\" they purred. \"They'll grow into a money tree!\""
      ],
      [
        "Page 7",
        "Pinocchio believed them and buried his coins. He waited and waited. But no tree grew — the tricksters had vanished! Jiminy shook his head. \"Oh dear,\" sighed Pinocchio. \"I should have listened.\" Home he hurried, feeling very small."
      ],
      [
        "Page 8",
        "At home, Geppetto asked gently, \"Where are your books, son?\" Pinocchio gulped. \"A-a big bird took them!\" he fibbed. Suddenly — boing! His nose grew longer. He told another fib. Boing! Longer still! Pinocchio gasped."
      ],
      [
        "Page 9",
        "\"Lies make your nose grow,\" chirped Jiminy kindly. Pinocchio's wooden cheeks burned. He took a deep breath. \"Papa, I traded my books. I'm sorry.\" Snap! His nose shrank right back. Geppetto hugged him tight and smiled."
      ],
      [
        "Page 10",
        "Days passed, and Pinocchio tried hard to be good. But one stormy morning, Geppetto went sailing to search for him and didn't come back. A fisherman whispered, \"A great whale swallowed his boat!\" Pinocchio's wooden heart ached."
      ],
      [
        "Page 11",
        "Brave little Pinocchio ran to the sea. Splash! In he jumped. Down, down into the big blue. There, inside a giant whale's belly, sat Geppetto with a tiny candle. \"My boy!\" he cried. \"You came for me!\""
      ],
      [
        "Page 12",
        "Pinocchio tickled the whale's nose with a feather. \"Ah… ah… CHOO!\" Out they flew on a great wave! They paddled to shore, laughing and soaked. Pinocchio held Geppetto close. \"I'll always tell the truth now, Papa.\""
      ],
      [
        "Page 13",
        "That night, a gentle blue fairy floated in on moonbeams. \"Brave, honest, and loving — you have earned your wish.\" Tingle-sparkle! Pinocchio was a real boy! Geppetto laughed and danced. And Jiminy chirped, \"Well done, little friend.\""
      ]
    ],
